Azure Load Balancer
Purpose: Distribute traffic across multiple VMs or backend servers.

Layer 4 (TCP/UDP) load balancer.
Distributes traffic based on IP and port.
Supports Internal and Public Load Balancer.
Provides high availability for applications.
Commonly used with VM Scale Sets.

Application Gateway
Purpose: Load balance and protect web applications.

Layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS) load balancer.
Supports URL-based routing.
Supports SSL termination.
Includes Web Application Firewall (WAF).
Ideal for web applications and APIs.

Traffic Manager
Purpose: Direct users to the best Azure region globally.

DNS-based global traffic routing.
Routes users to nearest or healthiest endpoint.
Supports multi-region deployments.
Provides disaster recovery capability.
Works across Azure and non-Azure endpoints.

Azure Front Door
Purpose: Global application delivery and acceleration.

Layer 7 global load balancer.
Uses Microsoft's global edge network.
Provides SSL offloading and acceleration.
Supports WAF and DDoS protection.
Improves application performance worldwide.


Layer 4 vs Layer 7
Layer 4 (Transport Layer)

Works with TCP/UDP traffic.
Does not inspect application content.
Faster and lower latency.
Routes based on IP and Port.
Example: Azure Load Balancer.

Layer 7 (Application Layer)

Understands HTTP/HTTPS traffic.
Can inspect URLs, headers, cookies.
Supports URL-based routing.
Supports SSL termination.
Example: Application Gateway, Front Door.


Layer 4 = IP + Port Based Routing
Layer 7 = Content + URL Based Routing

Application Gateway vs Load Balancer
Azure Load Balancer
Layer 4.
TCP/UDP traffic.
No URL-based routing.
No WAF.
Best for VMs and infrastructure traffic.

Application Gateway
Layer 7.
HTTP/HTTPS traffic.
Supports URL/path routing.
Includes WAF.
Best for websites and APIs.

Load Balancer → Infrastructure traffic (L4)
Application Gateway → Web traffic + WAF + URL routing (L7)


